Prerequisites

Before installing MySQL Router, verify that the following requirements have been met:

MySQL Server is installed.

MySQL InnoDB Cluster has been successfully configured.

A Cluster Administrator account (for example, clusteradmin) exists.

All cluster nodes can communicate with one another.

Firewall rules permit MySQL traffic.

Hostname resolution (DNS or /etc/hosts) is functioning correctly.

Network connectivity between Router and all cluster nodes has been verified.

Step 1 – Install MySQL Router

Install MySQL Router using the operating system package manager.

dnf install mysql-router -y

After the installation completes, verify the installed version.

mysqlrouter --version

If the version information is displayed successfully, the installation has completed correctly.

Step 2 – Create the Router Operating System User

For security reasons, MySQL Router should never run as the root user.

Instead, create a dedicated operating system account.

id mysqlrouter || useradd -r -s /sbin/nologin mysqlrouter

This command first checks whether the mysqlrouter user already exists.

If it does not exist, a new system account is created.

Parameter explanation:

-r creates a system account.

-s /sbin/nologin prevents interactive login.

Using a dedicated service account is considered an enterprise security best practice.

Step 3 – Bootstrap MySQL Router

After installation, MySQL Router has no knowledge of the InnoDB Cluster.

The bootstrap process retrieves cluster metadata and automatically configures the Router.

Execute the following command:

mysqlrouter --bootstrap clusteradmin@node1:3306 --user=mysqlrouter

Where:

clusteradmin is the Cluster Administrator account.

node1 is any active MySQL server within the cluster.

3306 is the MySQL Server port.

--user=mysqlrouter specifies the operating system account under which the Router service will run.

You will be prompted to enter the Cluster Administrator password.

Once authentication succeeds, the bootstrap process begins.

What Does Bootstrap Do?

Bootstrap is the most important configuration step for MySQL Router.

During this process, Router automatically performs the following tasks:

Retrieves cluster metadata.

Creates an internal Router account inside MySQL.

Stores authentication credentials securely.

Generates the Router configuration file.

Configures routing ports.

Creates runtime directories.

Configures logging.

Initializes metadata cache services.

In other words, nearly all Router configuration is completed automatically through a single command.

Generated Configuration Files

After a successful bootstrap, the primary configuration file is created at:

/etc/mysqlrouter/mysqlrouter.conf

A backup copy is also generated:

/etc/mysqlrouter/mysqlrouter.conf.bak

In production environments, these configuration files should be included in regular backup procedures.

Step 4 – Start the MySQL Router Service

Start the Router service.

systemctl start mysqlrouter

Enable the service to start automatically after system boot.

systemctl enable mysqlrouter

Verify the current service status.

systemctl status mysqlrouter

If the service status displays active (running), MySQL Router has started successfully and is ready for configuration validation.

